# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: slate-magazine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:slate-magazine/20-minutes-france] Rossel noted that the news outlet had 22.4 million monthly users while ratings firm Médiamétrie reported in 2017 that it received 16 million unique users per month.
[src:slate-magazine/20-minutes-france] In Greater Paris, Ipsos and CESP confirmed a circulation of 805,000 with a readership of 2,339,000.
[src:slate-magazine/20-minutes-france] The French *20 minutes* was launched in Paris on 15 March 2002, and spread to 11 other urban areas of France, including, in order of size, the cities of Marseille, Lyon, Toulouse, Nice, Nantes, Strasbourg, Montpellier, Bordeaux, Lille, Rennes and Grenoble.
[src:slate-magazine/20-minutes-france] Each edition includes both national pages and regional sections.
[src:slate-magazine/20-minutes-france] Since its launch, *20 minutes* has led the market of free French newspapers.
[src:slate-magazine/20-minutes-france] In March 2014, due to the fall of advertising revenues (-6% en 2013), TF1 and Bolloré, owners of *20 minutes*' competitors —*Metronews* and *Direct Matin*—, announced their willingness to buy *20 minutes* and merge their activities.
[src:slate-magazine/20-minutes-france] Since 2016, it's co‑owned and published by Rossel and Ouest‑France, after Norwegian media group Schibsted sold its shares.
[src:slate-magazine/20-minutes-france] The final edition of the paper version was distributed on 5 July 2024.
[src:slate-magazine/20-minutes-france] In January 2025, 20 Minutes got a new look, with a modern logo and clear visual styles for each section of the news.
[src:slate-magazine/20-minutes-france] The editorial focus has shifted to include more practical content, as well as lifestyle and entertainment.
[src:slate-magazine/20-minutes-france] It also features dedicated sections like "Vie Pro" and has plans to update its TV and social media video formats.
[src:slate-magazine/20-minutes-france] The shift to a fully digital format reflects changes in commuter behavior, with fewer people reading print during transit and more accessing news on mobile devices.
[src:slate-magazine/20-minutes-france] With approximately 20 million monthly users, *20 Minutes* is currently one of the most widely used online news platforms in France, particularly among younger, mobile-oriented audiences.
[src:slate-magazine/20-minutes-france] The name *20 minutes* refers to the amount of time it should take one to read this daily newspaper.
[src:slate-magazine/ad-age] The site AdCritic.com was acquired by The Ad Age Group in March 2002.
[src:slate-magazine/ad-age] In 2004, *Advertising Age* acquired *American Demographics* magazine.
[src:slate-magazine/ad-age] In 2007 Ad Age acquired the Thoddands Power 150, which is a top marketing blogs list.
[src:slate-magazine/ad-age] An industry trade magazine, *BtoB*, was folded into *Advertising Age* in January 2014.
[src:slate-magazine/ad-age] In 2017, the magazine shortened its name to *Ad Age*.
[src:slate-magazine/ad-age] In 1980, Henderson Advertising, founded in 1946 by James M.
[src:slate-magazine/ad-age] Henderson in Greenville, South Carolina, became the first agency outside New York or Chicago to be named Advertising Age's "Advertising Agency of the Year".
[src:slate-magazine/ad-age] Since 2016, Ad Age has been running an annual award called **Creativity 50** honoring the 50 most creative people in the advertising, marketing, technology and entertainment industries, in addition to top creative campaigns and the most innovative advertising.
[src:slate-magazine/ad-age] Past winners have also included entertainers such as Beyonce, David Bowie, Sia, Dwayne Johnson, James Corden, Donald Glover, Stephen Colbert and author Kelly Oxford.
[src:slate-magazine/ad-age] In June 1968, the magazine's editorial board generated controversy and significant discussion about gun control in the United States after it ran an editorial with the headline "Guns Must Go".
[src:slate-magazine/ad-age] The editorial was written in response to the assassination of Robert F.
[src:slate-magazine/ad-age] Immense reaction generated after its publication, including fierce backlash.
[src:slate-magazine/ad-age] The magazine's managing editor, Jarlath J.
[src:slate-magazine/ad-age] Graham, soon remarked that "all hell broke loose" after the publication of the editorial.
[src:slate-magazine/adobe-experience-cloud] On September 15, 2009, Adobe Systems announced its intention to purchase Omniture, Inc., a company specializing in online marketing and web analytics based in Orem, Utah.
[src:slate-magazine/adobe-experience-cloud] The acquisition, valued at $1.8 billion, was finalized on October 23, 2009.
[src:slate-magazine/adobe-experience-cloud] Post-acquisition, Omniture's offerings were progressively integrated into what is now known as Adobe's Digital Marketing Business Unit, alongside other acquisitions such as Day Software and Efficient Frontier.
[src:slate-magazine/adobe-experience-cloud] Adobe Experience Cloud, initially known as Adobe Marketing Cloud, was unveiled in October 2012 as part of Adobe's strategy to phase out the Omniture brand.
[src:slate-magazine/adobe-experience-cloud] The suite integrates products from the acquired company, Omniture, along with other services into a unified cloud service.
[src:slate-magazine/adobe-experience-cloud] Adobe Experience Cloud encompasses analytics, social, advertising, media optimization, targeting, web experience management, journey orchestration, and content management services, hosted on Microsoft Azure.
[src:slate-magazine/adobe-experience-cloud] The eight main applications are Adobe Analytics, Adobe Target, Adobe Social, Adobe Experience Manager, Adobe Media Optimizer, Adobe Campaign (both Classic and Standard versions), Audience Manager, and Primetime.
[src:slate-magazine/adobe-experience-cloud] In 2013, Adobe acquired Satellite TMS from Search Discovery and rebranded it as Adobe Dynamic Tag Management (Adobe DTM).
[src:slate-magazine/adobe-experience-cloud] Then launched Adobe Launch in 2018, its tag management system.
[src:slate-magazine/adobe-experience-cloud] Adobe announced the acquisition of Magento for $1.68 billion on May 21, 2018.
[src:slate-magazine/adobe-experience-cloud] This acquisition aimed to incorporate commerce features into the Adobe Experience Cloud.
[src:slate-magazine/adobe-experience-cloud] Later that same year, on September 20, Adobe acquired Marketo, a marketing automation company.
[src:slate-magazine/adobe-experience-cloud] By 2021, Adobe Experience Platform Launch was slated to be integrated into the Adobe Experience Platform as part of a broader suite of data collection technologies.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] As the second-largest advertising-trade publication, its main competitor is *Ad Age*.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] *Adweek* also operates the Adweek Blog Network, which was formed from the assets of Mediabistro.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] Related publications include *Brandweek,* *Adweek Magazine's Technology Marketing* (ISSN 1536-2272), and *Marketing Week* (ISSN 0892-8274).
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] In 2018, the company produced the first Brandweek, event, a first-of-its-kind summit held September 23–25, 2018 in Palm Springs, Calif.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] Subsequent summits have been held in Miami.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] *Brandweek* was also previously a weekly American marketing trade publication that was published between 1986 and April 2011.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] In 1990, Affiliated Publications Inc., which publishes *The Boston Globe*, agreed to acquire 80 percent of the outstanding common stock of A/S/M Communications Inc., which published *Adweek*.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] The magazine stabilized in the 1990s under Verenigde Nederlandse Uitgeverijen's BPI Communications (VNU, later known as Nielson).
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] In April 2008, Alison Fahey, *Adweek'*s editor of ten years, was promoted to publisher and editorial director.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] She was replaced as editor by Mike Chapman, formerly of the Economist Intelligence Unit and eMarketer.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] On June 2, 2020, Los Angeles–based investment firm Shamrock Capital acquired *Adweek* from Canadian private equity firm Beringer Capital, which had acquired Adweek in July 2016.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] On July 26, 2023, Will Lee was announced as *Adweek'*s CEO.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] On November 30, 2023, Zoë Ruderman was announced as Chief Content Officer and Drew Schutte as Chief Revenue Officer.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] On January 15, 2015, after the acquisition of its previous parent, Mediabistro, by Prometheus Global Media, *Adweek* formed the "Adweek Blog Network," which consists of several B2B blogs about aspects of the mass media industry.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] They include *AgencySpy*, which focuses on advertising news, *TVNewser*, which focuses on cable and broadcast TV and streaming news and *TVSpy*, which focuses on local television news.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] The most notable member of the blog network is *TVNewser*, which focuses on the American news media and broadcast industry.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] The site was founded as *CableNewser* by then–Towson University student Brian Stelter in January 2004, who maintained the site until joining *The New York Times* as a media reporter in July 2007.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] Former MSNBC producer Chris Ariens took on the role of editor in 2007 and is now Adweek's SVP and Editorial Director.
[src:slate-magazine/adweek] Each year Adweek honors companies and individuals in the marketing and media industry by giving out several different awards, such as the *Adweek 50,* *Brand Genius*, *Creative 100*, *Agency of the Year*, *Media Plan of the Year* and Marketing Vanguard.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The **American Broadcasting Company** (**ABC**) is an American commercial broadcast television and radio network that serves as the flagship property of the Disney Television Group division of the Walt Disney Company.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The youngest of the "Big Three" American television networks, the network is sometimes referred to as the **Alphabet Network,** as its initialism also represents the first three letters of the English alphabet in order.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC launched as a radio network in 1943, as the successor to the NBC Blue Network, which had been purchased by Edward J.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] It extended its operations to television in 1948, following in the footsteps of established broadcast networks CBS and NBC, as well as the lesser-known DuMont.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In the mid-1950s, ABC merged with United Paramount Theatres (UPT), a chain of movie theaters that formerly operated as a subsidiary of Paramount Pictures.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Leonard Goldenson, who had been the head of UPT, made the then-new television network profitable by helping to develop and green-light many successful television series.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC has eight owned-and-operated and more than 230 affiliated television stations throughout the United States and its territories.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC News, through ABC News Radio, provides news and feature content to over 1,900 affiliated radio stations.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC is headquartered on Riverside Drive in Burbank, California, directly across the street from Walt Disney Studios and adjacent to the Team Disney – Roy E.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The network maintains secondary offices at 7 Hudson Square in New York City's Lower Manhattan neighborhood, which houses its broadcast center and the headquarters of its news division, ABC News.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Until early 2025, the network's East Coast operations were based at 77 West 66th Street on the Upper West Side of Manhattan.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Since 2007, when ABC Radio (later known as Cumulus Media Networks) was sold to Citadel Broadcasting, ABC has reduced its broadcasting operations almost exclusively to television, though it continues to produce ABC News Radio, and a new ABC Radio (later renamed ABC Audio) was established in 2015.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In 1927, NBC operated a radio network called the NBC Blue Network.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] It became an independent radio (and eventually television) network known as the American Broadcasting Company (ABC) in 1943.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC later joined United Paramount Theatres forming American Broadcasting-Paramount Theatres (later American Broadcasting Companies, Inc.).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] After its venture into radio and television throughout the 1960s and 1970s and the purchase of ESPN in 1982, the company was acquired and merged with Capital Cities, forming Capital Cities/ABC in 1986.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The company was sold to the Walt Disney Company in 1996.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The ABC television network provides an average of 89 hours of network programming each week.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] It also offers 22 hours of prime-time programming to affiliated stations from 8:00 p.m. to 11:00 p.m.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Monday through Saturday (Eastern and Pacific Time) and 7:00 p.m. to 11:00 p.m. on Sundays.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Daytime programming is also provided from 11:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Eastern and Pacific weekdays (subtract 1 hour for all other time zones) (with a one-hour break at 12:00 p.m.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Eastern/Pacific for stations to air newscasts, locally produced programming or syndicated programs) featuring the talk-lifestyle shows *The View* and *GMA: The Third Hour*, and the soap opera *General Hospital*.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Late night features the weeknight talk show *Jimmy Kimmel Live!*.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC's daytime schedule features the talk show *The View*, news show *GMA: The Third Hour*, and the soap opera *General Hospital*.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Originally premiering in 1963, *General Hospital* is ABC's longest-running entertainment program.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In addition to the long-running *All My Children* (1970–2011) and *One Life to Live* (1968–2012), notable past soap operas seen on the daytime lineup include *Ryan's Hope*, *Dark Shadows*, *Loving*, *The City* and *Port Charles*.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC also aired the last nine years of the Procter & Gamble-produced soap *The Edge of Night*, following its cancellation by CBS in 1975.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC Daytime has also aired several game shows, including *The Dating Game*, *The Newlywed Game*, *Let's Make a Deal*, *Password*, *Split Second*, *The $10,000/$20,000 Pyramid*, *Family Feud*, *The Better Sex*, *Trivia Trap*, *All-Star Blitz* and *Hot Streak*.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Sports programming is provided on occasion, primarily on weekend afternoons and Saturday evenings.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In 2006, the ABC Sports division was shut down, with all sports telecasts on ABC since then being produced in association with sister cable network ESPN under the branding ESPN on ABC.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] General industry trends and changes in rights have prompted reductions in sports on broadcast television, with Disney preferring to schedule the majority of its sports rights on the networks of ESPN (until 2020).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Since 2020 ESPN has prioritized ABC with airings of its sports telecasts with occasional simulcasts and exclusive games of ESPN *Monday Night Football* broadcasts on ABC.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Since 2006, ABC has at least aired 10 weeks of primetime sports programming, and since 2020 has aired sports programming almost every week from September to May each year (with primetime encores and movies airing the remainder of the year).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC is also the broadcast television rightsholder of the National Hockey League (NHL), with its package (under the *NHL on ESPN* branding).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In this deal, ABC broadcasts at least 10 regular season games (mostly afternoon), the NHL All-Star Game, the NHL Stadium Series, and four Stanley Cup Finals.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] During college football season, ABC typically carries an afternoon doubleheader on Saturdays, along with the primetime *Saturday Night Football*.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC also airs coverage of selected bowl games.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC also airs Major League Baseball (MLB) games on select weekends as part of ESPN's MLB package.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Beginning in the 2015 NFL season, ESPN agreed to begin simulcasting/exclusively airing NFL games on ABC.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Thus, ABC is the only major broadcast network that carries games from all of the traditional "big four" sports leagues (MLB, NFL, NBA, NHL).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] During the late winter months, ABC airs both men's and women's college basketball games on weekend afternoons.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In the spring and summer months, ABC also airs games (usually on weekends) from the Women's National Basketball Association (WNBA), and is the broadcast home of the X Games and Little League World Series.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In 2015, ESPN's annual ESPY Awards presentation moved to ABC from ESPN.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Bolstered by Caitlyn Jenner accepting the inaugural Arthur Ashe Courage Award during the ceremony, the 2015 ESPY Awards' viewership was roughly tripled over the 2014 ceremony on ESPN.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] After the NFL signed a new contract with the Walt Disney Company, ABC will air Super Bowl LXI in 2027 and Super Bowl LXV in 2031.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC has not aired a Super Bowl since Super Bowl XL in 2006.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC holds the broadcast rights to the Academy Awards, Primetime Emmy Awards, and the Country Music Association Awards.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC has also aired the Miss America competition from 1954 to 1956, 1997 to 2004, and 2011 to 2018.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC also broadcasts the annual *Disney Parks Christmas Day Parade* special on Christmas morning.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Since 1974, ABC has generally aired *Dick Clark's New Year's Rockin' Eve* – a New Year's Eve special featuring music performances and coverage of festivities in New York's Times Square.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC is also among the broadcasters of the Tournament of Roses Parade (although as mentioned, the Rose Bowl Game now airs exclusively on ESPN as a College Football Playoff "New Year's Six" bowl).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC owns nearly all of its in-house television and theatrical productions made since the 1970s, except certain co-productions (for example, *The Commish* is now owned by the estate of its producer, Stephen Cannell).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] When the FCC imposed its Financial Interest and Syndication Rules in 1970, ABC proactively created two companies: Worldvision Enterprises as a syndication distributor, and ABC Circle Films as a production company.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] However, between the publication and implementation of these regulations, the separation of the network's catalog was made in 1973.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The broadcast rights to pre-1973 productions were transferred to Worldvision, which became independent in the same year.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The company has been sold several times since Paramount Television acquired it in 1999, and has most recently been absorbed into CBS Media Ventures (formerly CBS Television Distribution), a unit of Paramount Skydance, which owns the competitor CBS.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Nonetheless, Worldvision sold portions of its catalog, including the Ruby-Spears and Hanna-Barbera libraries, to Turner Broadcasting System (now a part of Warner Bros. parent company Warner Bros.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Paramount Skydance and WBD are currently in the process of the merger in 2026, effectively bringing together the surviving fragments of Worldvision back under one umbrella.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] According to David Zaslav, the acquisition is expected to close within 6-12 months, pending regulatory and shareholder approval.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] With Disney's 1996 purchase of ABC, ABC Circle Films was absorbed into Touchstone Television, a Disney subsidiary which in turn was renamed ABC Studios in 2007.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Also part of the library are most films in the David O.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Disney–ABC Domestic Television (formerly known as Buena Vista Television and 20th Television) handles domestic television distribution, while Disney–ABC International Television (formerly known as Buena Vista International Television) handles international television distribution.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Since its inception, ABC has had over 300 television stations that have carried programming from the network at various times throughout its history, including its first two owned-and-operated and affiliated stations, founding O&O WABC-TV and inaugural affiliate WPVI-TV.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] As of 2020, ABC has eight owned-and-operated stations, and current and pending affiliation agreements with 236 additional television stations encompassing 50 states, the District of Columbia, four U.S. possessions, Bermuda, and Saba.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] This makes ABC the largest U.S. broadcast television network by the total number of affiliates.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The network has an estimated national reach of 97.72% of all households in the United States (or 305,347,338 Americans with at least one television set).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC maintains affiliations with low-power stations (broadcasting either in analog or digital) in a few markets, such as Birmingham, Alabama (WBMA-LD), Lima, Ohio (WPNM-LD) and South Bend, Indiana (WBND-LD).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In some markets, including Lima and South Bend, these stations also maintain digital simulcasts on a subchannel of a co-owned/co-managed full-power television station.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Joseph's lone major network affiliate until 2011, when locally based News-Press & Gazette Company began establishing low-power affiliates of ABC's four English-language competitors and Telemundo on three low-power stations to end St.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] WWSB, KHGI, and WOTV serve areas that do not receive an adequate signal from their market's primary ABC affiliate.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC initially affiliated with WWSB to cover southern portions of the Tampa–St.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] WCVB-TV is licensed to Boston while WMUR-TV is licensed to Manchester, New Hampshire (which is officially part of the Boston market).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] WCVB is easily receivable in Manchester with a good antenna as well as having its news department that covers New Hampshire; it is the only station licensed to the state that does such.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Both WCVB and WMUR are owned by Hearst Television.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The Sinclair Broadcast Group is the largest operator of ABC stations by numerical total, owning or providing services to 28 full, primary ABC affiliates and two subchannel-only affiliates.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Sinclair owns the largest ABC subchannel affiliate by market size, WABM-DT2/WDBB-DT2 in the Birmingham market, which serves as repeaters of WBMA-LD (which itself is also simulcast on a subchannel of former WBMA satellite WGWW, owned by Sinclair partner company Howard Stirk Holdings).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Scripps Company is the largest operator of ABC stations in terms of overall market reach, owning 15 ABC-affiliated stations including affiliates in larger markets such as Cleveland (WEWS-TV), Phoenix (KNXV-TV), Detroit (WXYZ-TV), and Denver (KMGH-TV).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Through its ownership of Phoenix affiliate KNXV, Las Vegas affiliate KTNV-TV, and Tucson affiliate KGUN-TV, it is the only provider of ABC programming for the majority of Arizona (outside the Yuma–El Centro market) and Southern Nevada.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Scripps also owns and operates several ABC stations in the Mountain and Pacific time zones, including in Denver, San Diego (KGTV), Bakersfield, California (KERO-TV), and Boise, Idaho (KIVI-TV).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] At the time of Jimmy Kimmel's suspension in September 2025, among other properties owned by the two companies, Nexstar Media Group owned or provided services to 201 stations serving 116 markets, while Sinclair owned or provided services to 178 stations in 81 markets.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Individually, Sinclair and Nexstar were respectively the second- and fourth-largest owners of ABC stations, reaching 14.56% and 9.28% of American households respectively (with The E.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Scripps Company, with 17 affiliates covering 12.87% of the United States, being the third-largest).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] All of ABC's owned-and-operated stations and affiliates have had their facilities and studios, but transverse entities have been created to produce national programming.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] As a result, television series were produced by ABC Circle Films beginning in 1962 and by Touchstone Television beginning in 1985, before Touchstone was reorganized as ABC Studios in February 2007 and given its current name ABC Signature in August 2020.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Since the 1950s, ABC has had two main production facilities: the ABC Television Center (now The Prospect Studios) on Prospect Avenue in Hollywood, California, shared with the operations of KABC-TV until 1999, and the ABC Television Center, East, a set of studios located throughout New York City.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Additionally, Disney Television Animation has a facility on Empire Avenue near the Hollywood Burbank Airport.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In nearby Glendale, Disney/ABC also maintains the Grand Central Creative Campus, which houses other company subsidiaries, including the studios of KABC-TV and the Los Angeles bureau of ABC News.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC owned several facilities in New York, grouped mainly on West 66th Street, with the main set of facilities on the corner of Columbus Avenue.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] These facilities occupy a combined 105,000 square feet (9,800 m2) across two blocks with a total area of 159,000 square feet (14,800 m2).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC also owns 7, 17 and 47 West 66th Street, three buildings on a 375-by-100-foot (114 m × 30 m) plot.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The block of West 66th Street between Central Park West and Columbus Avenue, which houses the ABC News building, was renamed Peter Jennings Way in 2006 in honor of the then-recently deceased news anchor.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Disney formerly leased 70,000 sq ft (6,500 m2) at 157 Columbus Avenue, on the northern side of 67th Street.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC owns the Times Square Studios at 1500 Broadway, on land owned by a development fund for the 42nd Street Project.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Opened in September 1999, *Good Morning America* was broadcast from this facility until June 13, 2025.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC News had premises on West 66th Street, in a six-story building occupying a 196-by-379-foot (60 m × 116 m) plot at 121–135 West End Avenue.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] On July 9, 2018, the Walt Disney Company announced that it was selling its two West 66th Street campuses (except for the National Guard Amory) to Silverstein Properties and purchasing one square block of property in lower Manhattan to build a new New York-based broadcast center.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The building, known as 7 Hudson Square, opened in 2024 with The View being the first show to move to the new broadcast facility.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The Tamron Hall Show, ABC News, WABC-TV, ESPN, and Good Morning America all moved their operations to the new facility separately from January–June 2025.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC maintains several video on demand (VOD) services for delayed viewing of the network's programming, including a traditional VOD service called ABC on Demand, which is carried on most traditional cable and IPTV providers.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The Walt Disney Company is also a part-owner of Hulu, and has offered full-length episodes of most of ABC's programming through this streaming service since July 6, 2009.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In May 2013, ABC launched "WatchABC", a revamp of its traditional multi-platform streaming services encompassing the network's existing streaming portal at ABC.com and a mobile app for smartphones and tablet computers.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] This service provides full-length episodes of ABC programs and live streams of local affiliates in select markets (this was the first such offering by a U.S. broadcast network).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Live streams are only available to authenticated subscribers of participating pay television providers.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] WABC-TV New York and WPVI-TV Philadelphia were the first stations to offer streams of their programming on the service, with the six remaining ABC O&Os offering streams by the start of the 2013–14 season.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Hearst Television also reached a deal to offer streams of its ABC affiliates on the service, though as of 2016 these stations are only available for live-streaming for DirecTV subscribers.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In November 2015, it was reported that ABC had been developing a slate of original digital series for the WatchABC service, internally codenamed ABC3.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In July 2016, ABC re-launched its streaming platforms, dropping the WatchABC brand, adding a streaming library of 38 classic ABC series, and introducing 7 original short-form series under the blanket branding ABCd.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The most recent episodes of the network's shows are usually made available on the ABC app, Hulu, and ABC on Demand the day after their original broadcast.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In addition, ABC on Demand disallows fast forwarding of accessed content.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In 2021, ABC updated the app to allow app users to watch shows from ABC's sister networks: Freeform, FX, and National Geographic.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Free ad-supported streaming television channels were added to the ABC app in 2022 and 2023, including a 24-hour version of ESPN8 The Ocho and a seasonal channel dedicated to Freeform's 25 Days of Christmas original content.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] On August 23, 2024, Disney began notifying its carriage partners that it would discontinue the mobile and digital media player apps for ABC, along with DisneyNow, Freeform, FX, and National Geographic, effective September 23.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] However, TV Everywhere content would still be available via their respective websites in order to funnel viewers towards Disney+ and Hulu.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC's master feed is transmitted in 720p high-definition, the native resolution format for the Walt Disney Company's American television properties.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Although ABC has not fully transitioned to 1080p or ultra HD, some stations such as ABC affiliate station KNXV-TV in Phoenix, Arizona, transmit the network's programming at 1080p via an ATSC 3.0 multiplex stations, such as KASW with KNXV-TV.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Both new and returning scripted series were broadcast in high definition.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In 2011, *Extreme Makeover: Home Edition* was the last program on the network's schedule that was broadcast in 4:3 standard definition.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] All of the network's new programming has been presented in HD since January 2012.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The affiliate-syndicated Saturday morning educational and informative (E/I) block *Litton's Weekend Adventure* was the first children's program block on U.S. network television to feature programs available in HD upon its September 2011 debut.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The HD programming is broadcast in 5.1 surround sound.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] With this change, some programs also began positioning their main on-screen credits outside the 4:3 aspect ratio.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Gray-colored version of the logo from May 30, 2013 to August 8, 2021, was the main logo from September 14, 2018 onward.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Variants in gold, blue, and red were used from May 30, 2013 to September 13, 2018.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The ABC logo has evolved many times since the network's creation in 1943.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The network's first logo, introduced in 1946, consisted of a television screen containing the letters "T" and "V,” with a vertical *ABC* microphone in the center, referencing the network's roots in radio.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] When the ABC-UPT merger was finalized in 1953, the network introduced a new logo based on the FCC seal, with the letters "ABC" enclosed in a circular shield surmounted by a bald eagle.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In 1957, just before the television network began its first color broadcasts, the ABC logo consisted of a tiny lowercase *αbc* in the center of a large lowercase letter *α*, a design known as the ABC Circle A.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In 1962, graphic designer Paul Rand redesigned the ABC logo (nicknamed the "ABC Circle") into its current and best-known form, with the lowercase letters "αbc" enclosed in a single black circle.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The new logo debuted on-air on October 19 of the same year, but it was not until the following spring that it was fully adopted.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The letters are strongly reminiscent of the Bauhaus typeface designed by Herbert Bayer in the 1920s, but also share similarities with several other fonts, such as ITC Avant Garde and Horatio, and most closely resembling Chalet.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The logo's simplicity made it easier to redesign and duplicate, which was beneficial before the advent of computer graphics.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] A color version of the logo was also developed around 1963, and animated as a brief 10-second intro to be shown before the then-small handful of network programs broadcast in color (similar to the NBC "Laramie" peacock intro used during that era).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The "a" was rendered in red, the "b" in blue, and the "c" in green, against the same single black circle.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] A variant of this color logo, with the colored letters against a white circle, was also commonly used throughout the 1960s.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The 1970s and 1980s saw the emergence of many graphical imaging packages for the network which based the logo's setting mainly on special lighting effects then under development including white, blue, pink, rainbow neon, and glittering dotted lines.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Among the ABC Circle logo's many variants was a 1977 ID sequence that featured a bubble on a black background representing the circle with glossy gold letters, and was the first ABC identification card to simulate a three-dimensional appearance.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In 1983, for the 40th anniversary of the network's founding, ID sequences had the logo appear in a gold CGI design on a blue background, accompanied by the slogan "That Special Feeling" in a script font.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Ten years later, in 1993, the "ABC Circle" logo reverted to its classic white-on-black color scheme, but with gloss effects on both the circle and the letters, and a bronze border surrounding the circle.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The four-note signature has been updated with every television season thereafter until the 2020–21 season.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In 1999, ABC launched a web-based promotional campaign focused around its circle logo, also called 'the dot', in which comic book character Little Dot prompted visitors to "download the dot,” a program which would cause the ABC logo to fly around the screen and settle in the bottom-right corner.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The network hired the Troika Design Group to design and produce its 2001–02 identity, which continued using the black-and-yellow coloring of the logo and featured dots and stripes in various promotional and identification spots.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] On June 10, 2007, ABC began to phase in a new imaging campaign for the upcoming 2007–08 season, "Start Here".
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC introduced a revision to its logo and branding by Loyalkaspar for the 2013–14 season, the logo carried a simpler gloss design than the 2007 version, and had lettering closer-resembling Paul Rand's original version of the circle logo.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] A custom typeface inspired by the ABC logotype, ABC Modern, was also created for use in advertising and other promotional elements.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The logo was used in various color schemes, with a gold version used primarily for ABC's entertainment divisions, a red version used primarily for ESPN on ABC, steel blue and dark grey versions used primarily by ABC News, and all four colors used interchangeably in promotions.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Upon a reimaging by The New Blank for the 2018–19 season, the blue, red, and yellow variants were dropped, with the dark grey version becoming ABC's main logo.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Surrounding promotional elements adopted a circular "echo" motif and the new slogan "America's Network".
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Another revision to the logo was introduced on August 9, 2021, ahead of the 2021–22 season.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Designed by Trollbäck & Company, it is designed to adhere to flat design trends, and returns to a solid, two-dimensional design with smaller and bolder lettering.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The main logo is rendered in a dark, blue-gray color, while outlined and black-on-red variations are also used (such as for the on-screen bug and promotional usage respectively).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The 2021 rebrand also introduced a sonic logo that retains three out of the four notes of ABC's prior audio logo and was composed by YouTooCanWoo.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The Circle 7 logo, designed in 1962, is also commonly associated with ABC affiliates who broadcast on channel 7, including its flagship local stations WABC-TV (New York City), KABC-TV (Los Angeles), KGO-TV (San Francisco) and WLS-TV (Chicago).
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] This logo was intended to be used somewhat interchangeably by these stations with the main circular network logo and has itself also become an iconic symbol of the ABC network.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] KGO was the first of the ABC-owned stations to use the Circle 7 logo, starting on August 27, 1962, by the end of the year, the other ABC-owned stations began using the logo, and have continued to do so since.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The first attempts to internationalize the ABC television network dates to the 1950s, when Goldenson tried to use the same strategies he had in expanding UPT's theater operation to the international market.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Goldenson said that ABC's first international activity was broadcasting the coronation of Queen Elizabeth II in June 1953, CBS and NBC were delayed in covering the coronation due to flight delays.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Goldenson tried international investing, having ABC invest in stations in the Latin American market, acquiring a 51% interest in a network covering Central America and in 1959 established program distributor Worldvision Enterprises.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Goldenson also cited interest in Japan in the early 1950s, acquiring a 5% stake in two new domestic networks, the Mainichi Broadcasting System in 1951 and TV Asahi in 1957.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Goldenson also invested in broadcasting properties in Beirut in the mid-1960s.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The goal was to create a network of wholly and partially owned channels and affiliates to rebroadcast the network's programs.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In 1959, this rerun activity was completed with program syndication, with ABC Films selling programs to networks not owned by ABC.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The arrival of satellite television ended the need for ABC to hold interests in other countries, many governments also wanted to increase their independence and strengthen legislation to limit foreign ownership of broadcasting properties.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The second period of international expansion is linked to that of the ESPN network in the 1990s, and policies enacted in the 2000s by Disney Media Networks.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] These policies included the expansion of several of the company's U.S.-based cable networks including Disney Channel and its spinoffs Toon Disney, Playhouse Disney and Jetix, although Disney also sold its 33% stake in European sports channel Eurosport for $155 million in June 2000.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In contrast to Disney's other channels, ABC broadcasts in the United States with programming syndicated in other countries.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] The policy regarding wholly owned international networks was revived and on September 27, 2004, ABC announced the launch of ABC1, a free-to-air channel in the United Kingdom owned by the ABC Group.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] However, ABC1 could not attain sustainable viewership and was shut down in October 2007.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Prior to the ABC1 closure, on October 10, 2006, Disney–ABC Television Group entered into an agreement with satellite provider Dish TV to carry its ABC News Now channel in India.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] However, this operation was not put into effect.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] ABC's other slogans were also adopted by Nine during the 1980–2006 period, as secondary slogans complementing the "Still the One" slogan.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Nine's Wide World of Sports, the sports brand of Nine, is unrelated to ABC's Wide World of Sports.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Most Canadians have access to at least one U.S.-based ABC affiliate, either over-the-air (in areas located within proximity of the Canada–United States border) or through a cable, satellite or IPTV provider.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] Like Canada, ABC programming is available in Mexico through free-to-air affiliates in markets located within proximity to the Mexico–United States border whose signals are readily receivable over-the-air in border areas of northern Mexico.
[src:slate-magazine/american-broadcasting-company] In the Philippines, ABC maintained close ties with GMA Network and the unrelated Philippine network whose sharing the same abbreviation and more commonly known as TV5 regarding the content agreement with these networks.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] The **American Society of Magazine Editors** (**ASME**) is an industry trade group for magazine journalists and editors of magazines published in the United States.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] ASME includes the editorial leaders of most major consumer magazine in print and digital extensions.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] The group advocates on behalf of member organizations with respect to First Amendment issues and serves as a networking hub for editors and other industry employees.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] ASME started as an outgrowth of the editorial committee of the Magazine Publishers of America in 1963.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] The initial goal of the organization was to defend the First Amendment, protect editorial independence and support the development of journalism.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] ASME has sponsored the National Magazine Awards (also known as the Ellie Awards) since 1966, along with the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] The Ellie Awards honor print and digital magazines that consistently demonstrate superior execution of editorial objectives, innovative techniques, noteworthy journalistic enterprise, and imaginative art direction.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] In 1966, *Look* received the first award.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] *Money* received the first award for digital journalism in 1997.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] Magazine Editors' Hall of Fame and Creative Excellence Awards honor editors, writers, and artists for career-long contributions to magazine journalism.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] Honorees are chosen by the ASME board of directors.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] The ASME Best Cover Contest honors the most successful magazine covers of the year.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] The contest is two-fold: the ASME Best Cover Awards and the ASME Readers' Choice Awards.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] Each cover entered in the Best Cover Contest is eligible to win both a Best Cover Award and a Readers' Choice Award.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] ASME hosts the annual American Magazine Media Conference, every year in February, a meeting for magazine media leaders.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] It is sponsored by the Association of Magazine Media in association with ASME.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] The conference addresses issues of concern to editors and publishers of print and digital publications.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] Founded in 1967, the Magazine Internship Program places college juniors in internships at top consumer magazines for 10 weeks every summer.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] More than 250 alumni of this program now work in magazine media and include the editors in chief of major titles.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] To be eligible for membership into ASME, one must be employed by a print or digital magazine edited and distributed in the United States, this includes: senior editors, art directors and photography editors.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] There are also four categories of membership: Chief Editor, Editor, Retired Editor and ASME NEXT.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] Chief Editors, Editors and Retired Editors are entitled to all the privileges of ASME membership.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] ASME NEXT members are not eligible to vote in ASME elections.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] ASME is regulated by a 16-member board of directors, which serve 2-year terms.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] Directors may be selected for a second 2-year term upon election.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] Board elections are usually held during the first Wednesday in May at the ASME Annual Meeting.
[src:slate-magazine/american-society-of-magazine-editors] Currently, the chief executive of ASME is Sid Holt.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Applebaum has worked at *The Economist* and *The Spectator* magazines, and she was a member of the editorial board of *The Washington Post* (2002–2006).
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] She won the Pulitzer Prize for General Nonfiction in 2004 for *Gulag: A History*.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] She is a staff writer for *The Atlantic* magazine, as well as a senior fellow of the SNF Agora Institute and the School of Advanced International Studies at Johns Hopkins University.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Applebaum was born in Washington, D.C., to a reform Jewish family, the eldest of three daughters of Harvey M. and Elizabeth Applebaum.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Her father, a Yale alumnus, is senior counsel in the antitrust and international trade practices at Covington & Burling.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Her mother was a program coordinator at the Corcoran Gallery of Art.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] According to Applebaum, her great-grandparents immigrated to North America during the reign of Alexander III of Russia from what is now Belarus.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] After attending Sidwell Friends School in Washington, D.C., Applebaum entered Yale University; there she studied Soviet history under Wolfgang Leonhard during the fall semester of 1982.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] While an undergraduate, she spent the summer of 1985 in Leningrad, Soviet Union (now Saint Petersburg, Russia), an experience she says helped shape her opinions.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Applebaum received her B.A. from Yale in 1986 in history and literature.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] She received a two-year Marshall Scholarship at the London School of Economics, where she earned a master's degree in international relations (1987).
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] She also studied at St Antony's College, Oxford, before becoming a correspondent for *The Economist* and moving to Warsaw, Poland, in 1988.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In November 1989, Applebaum drove from Warsaw to Berlin to report on the collapse of the Berlin Wall.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] As foreign correspondent for *The Economist* and *The Independent*, she covered the fall of the Berlin Wall and the fall of communism.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In 1991 she returned to England to work for *The Economist*; she was later hired as the foreign editor and subsequently deputy editor of *The Spectator*, and later the political editor of the *Evening Standard*.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In 1994, she published her first book, *Between East and West: Across the Borderlands of Europe*, a travelogue that described the rise of nationalism across the new states of the former Soviet Union.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In 2001, she interviewed prime minister Tony Blair.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] She also undertook historical research for her book *Gulag: A History* (2003), about the Soviet prison camp system, which won the 2004 Pulitzer Prize for General Nonfiction.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] It was also nominated for a National Book Award, the *Los Angeles Times* book award, and the National Book Critics Circle Award.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Applebaum has been a member of the editorial board of *The Washington Post*, and was a columnist for the newspaper for 17 years.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In addition, she was an adjunct fellow at the American Enterprise Institute, a conservative think tank.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Her second history book, *Iron Curtain: The Crushing of Eastern Europe 1944–56*, was published in 2012 by Doubleday (in the US) and Allen Lane (in the UK); it was nominated for a National Book Award and shortlisted for the 2013 PEN/John Kenneth Galbraith Award.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] From 2011 to 2016, she created and ran the Transitions Forum at the Legatum Institute, an international think tank and educational charity based in London.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] With *Foreign Policy* magazine she created Democracy Lab, a website focusing on countries moving toward or away from democracy; this later became Democracy Post at *The Washington Post*.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In 2016, she left Legatum because of its stance on Brexit after the Euroskeptic Philippa Stroud was appointed CEO; Applebaum then joined the London School of Economics (LSE) as a professor of practice at the Institute for Global Affairs.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] At the LSE, she ran Arena, a program on disinformation and 21st-century propaganda.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In 2019, she moved the program to the SNF Agora Institute at Johns Hopkins University.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In 2017, she published her third history book, *Red Famine: Stalin's War on Ukraine,* a history of the Holodomor (the 1932–33 human-made famine in Soviet Ukraine).
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] The book won the Lionel Gelber Prize and the Duff Cooper Prize, making her the only author to win the Duff Cooper Prize twice.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In November 2019, *The Atlantic* announced that Applebaum would join the publication as a staff writer starting in January 2020.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] She was included in *Prospect* magazine's 2020 list of the top 50 thinkers for the COVID-19 era.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In July 2020, her book *Twilight of Democracy: The Seductive Lure of Authoritarianism* was published.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Partly a memoir and partly political analysis, it was on the bestseller lists of *Der Spiegel* magazine and *The New York Times*.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Applebaum is a member of the Council on Foreign Relations.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] She is on the boards of the National Endowment for Democracy and Renew Democracy Initiative.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] She is also on the editorial boards of *The American Interest* magazine and the *Journal of Democracy*.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] She was a member of the international board of directors of the Institute for War and Peace Reporting.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In addition, she was a Senior Adjunct Fellow at the Center for European Policy Analysis (CEPA), where she co-led a major initiative aimed at countering Russian disinformation in Central and Eastern Europe (CEE).
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In 2000, Applebaum described the links between the then-new president of Russia, Vladimir Putin; the former Soviet leader Yuri Andropov; and the former KGB agency.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In 2008, she began speaking about *Putinism* as an anti-democratic ideology.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] However, most people at the time still considered Putin a pro-Western pragmatist.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Applebaum has been a vocal critic of Western conduct toward the Russian military intervention in Ukraine.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In an article in *The Washington Post* on March 5, 2014, she maintained that the US and its allies should not continue to enable "the existence of a corrupt Russian regime that is destabilizing Europe", writing that Putin's actions had violated "a series of international treaties".
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] On March 7 in another article, in *The Daily Telegraph*, discussing an information war, Applebaum argued that "a robust campaign to tell the truth about Crimea is needed to counter Moscow's lies".
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] At the end of August, she asked whether Ukraine should prepare for "total war" with Russia and whether central Europeans should join them.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Critics of Applebaum's, including journalist Glenn Greenwald, have called her a "warmonger" and a "neocon".
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In 2014, she wrote a review of Karen Dawisha's book *Putin's Kleptocracy* for *The New York Review of Books*; in it, she asked whether "the most important story of the past twenty years might not, in fact, have been the failure of democracy, but the rise of a new form of Russian authoritarianism".
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] She has described the "myth of Russian humiliation" and argued that NATO and EU expansion have been a "phenomenal success".
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In July 2016, before the US election, she wrote about connections between Donald Trump and Russia; she wrote that Russian support for Trump was part of a wider Russian political campaign designed to destabilize the West.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Applebaum's article in *The Washington Post* on October 14, 2018, "This Is Why So Many Journalists Are At Risk Today" highlighted attacks on press freedom by "authoritarian and autocratic regimes".
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In "Kill the Messenger: Why Palestine radio and TV studios are fair targets in the Palestine/Israeli war", Applebaum justified the bombing of the official Palestinian media and said that it was "a combatant—and therefore a legitimate target—in a painful, never-ending, low-intensity war".
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] But in a 2024 interview, she denied that "radio stations or television stations are actually legitimate military targets".
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Applebaum has written about the history of central and eastern Europe, Poland in particular.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] She has written essays on the Polish filmmaker Andrzej Wajda; the dual Nazi–Soviet occupation of central Europe; and why it is inaccurate to define *Eastern Europe* as a single entity.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Applebaum wrote about a 2014 Russian smear campaign against her while she was writing heavily about the Russian annexation of Crimea.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] She said that dubious online material was eventually recycled by semi-respectable American pro-Russia websites.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Applebaum argued in 2015 that Facebook should take responsibility for spreading false stories and help "undo the terrible damage done by Facebook and other forms of social media to democratic debate and civilized discussion all over the world".
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Applebaum has been a member of the advisory panel for the organization Global Disinformation Index.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Applebaum endorsed Hillary Clinton for president in July 2016, because Trump is "a man who appears bent on destroying the alliances that preserve international peace and American power".
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Applebaum wrote a *Washington Post* column in March 2016 that led the Swiss newspaper *Tages-Anzeiger* and the German magazine *Der Spiegel* to interview her.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] These articles appeared in December 2016 and January 2017.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] She wrote that the international populist movement frequently called "far right" or "alt-right" is not *conservative* as this term has traditionally been defined.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In January 2022, Applebaum was invited to testify before the Foreign Affairs Committee of the US House of Representatives; the committee hearing was entitled "Bolstering Democracy in the Age of Rising Authoritarianism".
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In 1992, Applebaum married Radosław Sikorski, who was later Poland's Minister of National Defence, Minister of Foreign Affairs, Marshal of the Sejm, and a member of the European Parliament.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Sikorski is currently Minister of Foreign Affairs in Donald Tusk's Third Cabinet.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] Applebaum gained Polish citizenship in 2013; she speaks Polish and Russian in addition to English.
[src:slate-magazine/anne-applebaum] In July 2025, Applebaum delivered the opening address at the Salzburg Festival.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] As of 2025, the magazine is both ad-supported and has a membership model with a metered paywall.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] It is known, and sometimes criticized, for adopting contrarian views, which gave rise to the term "Slate Pitches".
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] It has a generally liberal editorial stance.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2004, the magazine was purchased by The Washington Post Company.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] An agreement in the purchase stipulated that the MSN website would continue to redirect to *Slate*.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] It introduced *Slate V* in 2007, an online video magazine website.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] Later, in 2008, The Washington Post Company launched The Slate Group, an online publishing entity, to manage *Slate* and other online magazines.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] The same year, *Slate* launched *The Root*, an African American news site, and "The Big Money", a business news website.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2011, *Slate* switched their content management system from Gutenberg to Adobe CQ5.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In the same year, the magazine laid off several high-profile journalists, including co-founder Jack Shafer and Timothy Noah (author of the *Chatterbox* column).
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] At the time, it had around 40 full-time editorial staff.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2012, then-editor David Plotz spoke at South by Southwest on *Slate*'s efforts in running long-form journalism.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] Plotz discussed their commitment for all editors to spend four to six weeks each year to focus on a project, nicknamed "Fresca" projects, instead of working on news output.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] *Slate* also launched the "Slate Book Review", a monthly books section edited by Dan Kois, and a dedicated ad sales team.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2013, the magazine was redesigned under the guidance of design director Vivian Selbo.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] After The Washington Post Company sold The Washington Post to Jeff Bezos in 2013, *Slate*'s parent company was renamed to Graham Holdings, which continued to own the magazine *Slate*.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2014, it was estimated that the website had 30 million visitors monthly.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] The same year, *Slate* introduced a paywall system called "Slate Plus", offering ad-free podcasts and bonus materials.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] A year later, it had attracted 9,000 subscribers, generating about $500,000 in annual revenue.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] By September 2014, *Slate* became profitable after preceding years had seen layoffs and falling ad revenue.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] *Slate* then moved all content behind a metered paywall for international readers in June 2015, attributing the change to advertisers targeting domestic readers.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2018, *Slate* staff members joined the Writers Guild of America, East.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] After union members authorized a strike, *Slate* agreed to a three-year collective bargaining agreement in January 2019.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2021, Mike Pesca, host of the podcast *The Gist*, was suspended from *Slate* after a Slack discussion on Donald G.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] McNeil Jr. and the usage of a racial slur, ultimately parting ways and taking his podcast independent.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] On September 16, 2025, *Slate* filed a lawsuit against Google over alleged antitrust violations.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In February 2009, slate.fr, a French-language offshoot of *Slate*, was launched.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] Its five founders were: Le Monde editors Jean-Marie Colombani and Éric Leser, Libération and 20 minutes editor Johan Hufnagel, Les Echos editor Éric Le Boucher, and political advisor Jacques Attali.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] The founders held fifty percent in the publishing company, while The Washington Post Company held 15 percent.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2011, slate.fr started a separate site covering African news, *Slate Afrique*, with a Paris-based editorial staff.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] Since 2006, *Slate* has been known for publishing contrarian pieces arguing against commonly held views about a subject, giving rise to the #slatepitches Twitter hashtag in 2009.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] The *Columbia Journalism Review* defined *Slate* pitches as "an idea that sounds wrong or counterintuitive proposed as though it were the tightest logic ever".
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2014, *Slate*'s then editor-in-chief, Julia Turner, acknowledged that a reputation for counterintuitive arguments forms part of *Slate*'s "distinctive" brand, but argued that the hashtag misrepresents the site's journalism.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2019, *Slate* editors such as David Plotz said that the *Slate* pitch had become difficult due to the polarizing politics of the Trump administration.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2022, *The New York Times* reported that anonymous *Slate* staffers felt that the publication's reputation for contrarian views had diminished over the years.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] Former Slate writer Matthew Yglesias concurred with this reporting, stating that the journalism industry had become homogeneous in recent times.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] According to the Nieman Foundation for Journalism, *Slate* has been involved in podcasts "almost from the very beginning" of the medium.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] Its first podcast, *Political Gabfest*, was released in 2005 and was inspired by *Slate*'s editorial conference calls.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] *Slate* podcasts have gotten longer over the years.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] The original *Gabfest* ran 15 minutes; by 2012, most ran about 45 minutes.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2012, it was reported that *Slate*'s podcasts had the highest advertisement and sell-through rates of their content on account of high user engagement.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] By June 2012, *Slate* had expanded their lineup to 19 podcasts, with *Political Gabfest* and *Culture Gabfest* being the most popular.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] This count had shrunk to 14 by February 2015, with all receiving six million downloads per month.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2018, it offered a slate of 25 podcasts.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] The Nieman Foundation for Journalism regarded the outlet as the "web's oldest living magazine".
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2004, *The New York Times* opined that the publication produced "well-regarded journalism".
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2010, the *Columbia Journalism Review* commended *Slate*'s high-quality editorial standards and praised its usage of interactive and multimedia content, calling them "consistently innovative, and often a big hit with readers".
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2019, *The New York Times* wrote that *Slate* was known for "counterintuitive analysis and its many podcasts".
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2022, Katie Robertson of the *New York Times* noted *Slate* was known for its "smart analysis, interesting debate and top-tier journalistic talent".
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] In 2003, *Slate* won the National Magazine Award (NMA) for General Excellence.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] *Slate* was also nominated for four digital National Magazine Awards in 2011 and won the NMA for General Excellence.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] Between 2009 and 2014, *Slate* was nominated for an NMA 14 times, winning the award twice.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] *Slate* received an NMA for general excellence in 2016.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] *Slate*'s investment in podcasts has led to receiving some awards, including *Slow Burn* and *Political Gabfest*.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] On June 7, 2001, *Slate* published an article by Jay Forman of a practice of fisherman from an island in the Florida Keys of fishing for rhesus monkeys.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] *The Wall Street Journal* and *The New York Times* found the claim to be a hoax after investigation.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] Later, Forman admitted to his editor, Jack Shafer, that his claim had been fabricated.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] Michael Kinsley was *Slate*'s founder and served as its first editor-in-chief from 1996 to 2002.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] He was followed by Jacob Weisberg, who held the position from 2002 to 2008.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] Afterward, David Plotz became editor until July 2014, when he was replaced by Julia Turner.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] After Turner resigned in 2019 to join the Los Angeles Times, Jared Hohlt became editor on April 1, 2019.
[src:slate-magazine/slate-magazine] Former HuffPost editor Hillary Frey was named as the magazine's new editor-in-chief in May 2022.
